Chapter 0
Introduction
These notes cover the core introductory topics in linear algebra. In particular, it deﬁnes and states the major theorems for
ﬁnite-dimensional vector spaces, as well as deﬁning important terms for all mathematics such as eigenvalues, inner products,
operator theory, and more.
The lecture notes are based oﬀ two main sources. The overall outline and the major statements of theorems and deﬁnitions
are based oﬀ lecture notes from Dr. Várilly-Alvarado during the Fall 2019 teaching of Rice’s course MATH 354 – Honors Linear
Algebra. These notes are supplemented by notes and exercises from Axler’s Linear Algebra Done Right.

1.2 Proofs by Induction
Theorem 1.2.1: Principle of Mathematical Induction II
Let P (n) be a statement indexed by n ∈ N. Suppose that
1. P(1) is true. (The base case)
2. If P (k) is true for some k ∈ N, then P (k + 1) is true. (The inductive hypothesis)
Then P (n) is true for all n ∈ N.
Theorem 1.2.2: Principle of Mathematical Induction III
Let Q(n) be a statement indexed by n ∈ N. Suppose that
1. Q(k
0

∈ N. (The base case)
2. If Q(k) is true for some k ∈ N, then Q(k + 1) is true. (The inductive hypothesis)
Then Q(n) is true for all n ≥ k

Theorem 2.6.1
Every spanning list in a vector space can be reduced to a basis of the vector space.

Every linearly independent list of vectors in a ﬁnite-dimensional vector space can be extended to a basis of the vector space.
Theorem 2.6.2: Soulmate space
Let (V, F, +, ·) be a ﬁnite dimensional vector space. let U ⊂ V be a subspace. Then there exists a W ⊂ V such that
U ⊕ W = V
Note that W is a ﬁnite-dimensional vector space.
